question: weaknesses
comment_clean: This course was very poorly executed. 1.) The course followed the flipped classroom methodology, but why? The entire course from day one was set up so that the responsibility of getting and digesting the material was placed squarely on the student (The flipped classroom methodology) and class time was only used for review of what the student should have taught themselves (in some cases in relatively shallow detail relative the level presented in the chapter or needed for the HW) and reviewing the homework if there were specific questions that someone had. I'm unsure why this approach was taken as it put a lot of work on the student to get and digest the information in addition to doing the immense amount of homework assigned almost every class (More on this in another section). To be frank, if I was interested in the topic of logic, I could have purchased the textbook and worked through it in my spare time and gotten an equivalent if not better education than I did by taking this course (As this was essentially all the course was), with the added benefit of getting to choose the amount of work I did or was needed to understand a given topic. 2.) Far too much homework In total, we were assigned 1,179 required problems for homework throughout the course, which correlates to an average of 84.21 problems per week (excluding weeks 9 and 14 which were midterms and break respectively), where the max assigned in a single week was 159 problems. This workload is further compounded by the fact that the chapter readings were assigned to be done by the student before each class in addition to all quizzes being done outside of class (To his credit, when the problems per week are graphed, a decline can be noticed in correlation to when quizzes are assigned). It is my understanding that the professor was approached by several students saying that the workload was a little intense and asking for him to consider reducing it, to which he said that he would. The workload was never reduced. I understand that mastery requires practice, but at what point does practice become beating a dead horse? The defense will be that if there were a lot of questions then they were short, but how this is simply not the case, and even if it were, there is still a non-trivial amount of time associated with doing them in addition to the other responsibilities of the class. 3.) Poor use of class time This was touched on some in the previous sections but class time ideally should have been used to lecture over the material that was expected to be learned by the student in enough depth that the homework was doable (rather than relying on the student to essentially teach it to themselves) and for quizzes (If they're take-home, homework should have been paused) and exams (Ideally would have fit into 1 class period but not overly problematic that they didn't). These problems ultimately lead to not reading the chapters in depth like I had in the beginning and only skimming them to answer specific questions, trying to get the homework done as quickly as possible as I viewed it as a chore once I got past the point of feeling like it was sufficient to learn the material (typically happened in 7 to 12 questions), and not being overly motivated to go to class (typically only 4 or 5 people regularly showed up to class out of a class of 9 or so) as I felt that I wouldn't gain much from the shallow coverage of the material that would be offered after doing the 20-50 questions of homework or that I should instead use that time to get caught up on homework I had fallen behind on.

question: weaknesses
comment_clean: It really puts students down when the only communication we receive from our experiential office is an email telling us how unprofessional we are and how disappointed we are making ONU. I feel that at this point in rotations, if there are students who are consistently struggling with professionalism or other things, they should be reach out to individually and assisted. Speaking this way to the whole class when most of us get great feedback month after month can be really draining. Most of us are doing our best to improve professionally and make ONU look good, but it really brings down motivation when we get only negative/threatening communications and no encouragement. I understand that in the real world our bosses will probably also mostly provide criticism with little praise, because that's how the world works. I just firmly believe that if the experiential office is finding themselves continuously frustrated month after month with certain students' performances, they should begin reaching out to these students one-on-one to see what is going on and how to help them.

question: weaknesses
comment_clean: The weakness of this course was fundamentally divided into two parts that interlink: organization and applied skills. The outcomes of this course were confused to say the least. At many times it felt like a refresher of research methods. That in itself is not an entirely bad thing as a refresher of the skills discussed are useful for the purposes of writing a thesis. However, the application of these lessons felt lacking. Aside from being asked to submit work for our thesis we never really had the opportunity to work on them. The class felt that we were supposed to just absorb what we were being told and tact it onto our thesis. This left the class feeling more like research methods than an actual introduction to thesis writing. For those of us (most of the class) who already took reserach methods we really did not gain anything. Another weakness was the class was structured far more as a research methods class rather than a thesis. It felt that theory areas (often important for political science) were largely ignored in favor of purely quantitative work. It felt as though little attention was given to the wider design tools of a thesis. Another problem is that the professor often can come across as usurping student papers to transform it to their preferences against the wishes of the student.

question: weaknesses
comment_clean: I have three things: 1) Professor likes to make connections with other topics, which is lovely, but I think he assumes legal educations are more standardized than they are in practice. For example, one time he was trying to connect with a Civil Procedure principle that we were taught as _domicile,_ but he was looking for a different word (I don't remember much), so it looked like we just didn't know. Also, sometimes you forget things and then relearn them for the bar, and that's okay. I think the connection is good, but the expectations involved could be more flexible. 2) I really appreciate that Professor Baez tries to foster discussion, but I think sometimes he gets dissapointed if we don't come up with a bunch of different answers (like, recently we've been covering amortization and like-kind exchanges with number answers, and he'll want to put a bunch of numbers on the board, but we only come up with 2 or 3, and one of them is typically right, so I think he doesn't need to push so hard to get a diversity of answers. Although, teaching a class without a lot of response from students is also difficult). 3) Also, Professor Baez sometimes makes a mistake that I feel like is common with well-organized professors who rely on lots of class back-and-forth: Sometimes he's looking for an answer, and so he doesn't hear the student's whole answer, or quite register what they said. So, like, if he's looking for an answer but wants to talk about it one step at a time, but a student gives the full answer right away, he might latch on to the part he was looking for or recognizes first, and ask the student the next part. The student then assumes that part of what they said was wrong and has to search for another answer, and it feels awkward. But I guess I don't know how avoidable that really is, and its definitely not the end of the world.

question: weaknesses
comment_clean: My biggest complaint about this course was a lack of consistency. Maybe it was a result of inconsistency from the city of Kenton. Maybe it was a result of the flexibility provided for students to choose their own routes and have completely different design processes. Regardless of the reason, it seemed like the advisors were often on different pages when it came to expectations for their capstone group. I was told that faculty from the civil department met once a week and most weeks held a discussion about this capstone course. If this was indeed the case, you would think that the expectations would be similar and only differ as a result of the different goals and design processes of each capstone group. Instead, I often got the impression that each advisor had very different expectations for their capstone group when it came time to have advisor meetings or present for a PRB. A little more consistency throughout the year would have been much less confusing and possibly even yielded better results from the capstone groups.

Maybe do a topic workshop day early in semester where you have kids write down their passions/interest/life events/etc and then break those down into lots and lots of smaller ideas. This will give students enough ideas for the ENTIRE semester. Sometimes it was hard to just get a topic going. -I think the inspiration we received that last day of 'real class' on 12/1 could've been beneficial if it was sprinkled throughout the semester. Sometimes it felt like were just there to produce a good speech & I missed out the larger goal of how public speaking & confidence is just good for life! Maybe Dr. can add in more times of honest motivation even when the work is tough/tedious.

question: improved
comment_clean: Like most professors, he sometimes asks open-ended questions that rely on inferences or outside knowledge and you sort of have to read his mind. I think its an attempt to get us to think critically, which is a fair teaching tool, but I think its okay for some of these questions to be rhetorical and for him to explain, especially because when you ask questions like _why would they structure their company this way? what is the benefit,_ there's so many answers, and also different levels of specificity he could be looking for, and its easy to get discouraged because the answer you thought was right wasn't close enough, or other people's answers went in a different direction than you were thinking. Like, the answers could have to do with civil liability, federal taxes, management ease, or be an answer as general as _for the money,_ and I don't know that there's a good way to indicate what exactly you're looking for when you ask those kinds of broad questions.

question: weaknesses
comment_clean: ONU struggles with sharing information to students about job opportunities/residencies. I am not saying they do not provide opportunities to meet but they provide no guidance to PHORcas, submitting transcripts (the instructions were missing VERY crucial information). I think this can fixed by having P6s talk to the P5s when we are coming back to boot camp. A simple breakout session to those who want to help would help the next class immensely. Lastly, I feel the relationship between the experiential office and the P6 classes needs to drastically improve. Consistent threats of grade dropping, failing rotations, and an overall adversarial relationship does not build a productive relationship/build prepared pharmacists. Students are scared in the first place for these rotations and ONU consistently threatening to drop grades or fail rotations does not help anyone. My suggestion is to have these conversations on a al level. I am not saying to have a one on one session with every student but those who are struggling might need help.

comment_clean: Please get rid of the exams, they didn't have anything to do with the actual labs and were more about trying to remember material from Fluid Mechanics and Thermo. comment_clean: -The progression of the speeches (from Self-Intro--> Persuasive) was very well planned out. The increase in demand from the rubrics for each speech was very well planned out too. Sometimes it seemed like advisors were contradicting each other or even themselves in terms of guiding students to the next PRB. Advisors should not be expected to contribute to the capstone project itself. They also shouldn't be responsible for making the students' workload easier by guiding them step by step by step from one PRB to the next. Still, I think consistent guidance and feedback was something that was lacking at times this semester from group to group.

comment_clean: One thing that I believe would be extremely beneficial for incoming APPE students would be a simple, streamlined, official checklist of the yearly and monthly requirements that are needed throughout the APPE year. There is a lot of conflicting information on CORE and in emails surrounding how many of each requirement/project we need throughout the year and I think the Experiential Office putting together up one sheet of paper (in a check-list format or something of the like) of what all is needed throughout the year and what all is needed throughout each month would be extremely helpful for students. Additionally, as I understand the purpose of the monthly emails of what to improve on, I must say that it is a bit of a confidence buster for most of us to read. I understand that those concerns are happening and I agree with the importance of addressing them, however I think it would be more helpful to the affected individuals and less hurtful to others to address the specific concerns with the specific students they are about. I have gotten really positive feedback from all of my preceptors about my APPE performance so far which I am very proud of, but seeing those harsh emails and getting no _good job_ to those of us who are doing well is really quite frustrating. I work hard and am trying my best on APPEs and I feel like those emails really discredit the hard work that the majority of us are putting in throughout this challenging year.
